./specs/t-010@20260408t223256zb-spec.md:34:4. If `ollama_health()` raises, `/status` and heartbeat degrade gracefully instead of crashing.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256za-spec.md:5:The live daemon has direct Ollama invocation and basic low-level health helpers, but it does not yet expose one daemon-local helper that summarizes both configured Ollama sockets. This subtask needs a synchronous `ollama_health()` helper in the daemon that queries ports `11434` and `11435` and returns stable per-instance status, loaded model names, and measured response latency for later `/status` and `/local` integration.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256za-spec.md:9:- Add a daemon-local `ollama_health()` helper in `my-claw/tools/cypherclaw_daemon.py`.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256za-spec.md:11:- Reuse the existing `my-claw/tools/ollama_health.py` helpers for health and model discovery instead of introducing a new HTTP client or dependency.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256za-spec.md:27:1. `cypherclaw_daemon.ollama_health()` returns a stable JSON-serializable summary for both Ollama sockets `11434` and `11435`.
./CHANGELOG.md:6:- Wired `ollama_health()` into the `/status` Telegram command and half-hour heartbeat so operators can see per-socket Ollama health, loaded models, and latency without SSH.
./CHANGELOG.md:7:- Added daemon-local `ollama_health()` dual-socket reporting for ports `11434` and `11435`, including per-instance loaded models and measured probe latency.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256zc-spec.md:5:`ollama_health()` is now available in the daemon and visible in Telegram `/status`, but operators still do not have the dedicated Telegram `/local` command promised by the R750 local-LLM plan. The current tree also has no shared status JSON endpoint for `/local` to consume. As a result, there is no direct operator command that focuses on local model availability, loaded models, and Ollama socket health.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256zc-spec.md:9:1. Add a shared daemon status snapshot helper in `my-claw/tools/cypherclaw_daemon.py` that returns the core `/status` counters plus the guarded `ollama_health()` payload.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256zc-spec.md:17:- If `ollama_health()` raises unexpectedly, both the shared status snapshot and `/local` must degrade to an explicit unavailable message instead of crashing.
./specs/t-010@20260408t223256zc-spec.md:34:   VERIFY: `pytest tests/test_local_command_runtime.py::test_local_command_runtime_renders_ollama_health -q`
